[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/amazon-kinesis] Amazon Kinesis was launched by Amazon Web Services (AWS) in November 2013 as a managed service for processing and analyzing real-time streaming data at a large scale.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/amazon-kinesis] The service was introduced to address the growing need for businesses to process and analyze data as it was generated, rather than in batches, allowing for real-time insights and decision-making.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/amazon-kinesis] Since its launch, the Amazon Kinesis family of services has expanded to include four main components: Kinesis Data Streams, Kinesis Data Firehose, Kinesis Data Analytics, and Kinesis Video Streams.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/amazon-kinesis] Each of these components serves a specific purpose in the processing and analysis of real-time streaming data.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/amazon-kinesis] In August 2015, AWS announced the availability of Kinesis Data Firehose, a fully managed service for delivering real-time streaming data to destinations such as Amazon S3, Amazon Redshift, and Amazon Elasticsearch.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/amazon-kinesis] A year later in August 2016, AWS launched Kinesis Data Analytics, enabling customers to analyze streaming data in real time using standard SQL queries.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/amazon-kinesis] AWS introduced Kinesis Video Streams, a fully managed service for securely capturing, processing, and storing video streams for analytics and machine learning applications, was introduced by AWS in November 2017.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/amazon-kinesis] Amazon Kinesis is composed of four main services: Kinesis Data Streams, Kinesis Data Firehose, Kinesis Data Analytics, and Kinesis Video Streams.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/amazon-kinesis] Kinesis Data Streams is a scalable and durable real-time data streaming service that captures and processes gigabytes of data per second from multiple sources.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/amazon-kinesis] It enables the storage and processing of data in real time, making it useful for applications that require immediate insights, such as monitoring and alerting.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/amazon-kinesis] Kinesis Data Firehose is a fully managed service for delivering real-time streaming data to destinations such as Amazon S3, Amazon Redshift, Amazon Elasticsearch, and AWS-partner data stores.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/amazon-kinesis] With Data Firehose, users can configure and scale data delivery without manual intervention.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/amazon-kinesis] Kinesis Data Analytics enables the analysis of streaming data in real time using standard SQL or Apache Flink.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/amazon-kinesis] Kinesis Video Streams is a fully managed service for securely capturing, processing, and storing video streams for analytics and machine learning.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/amazon-kinesis] It supports multiple video codecs and streaming protocols, making it suitable for various use cases, such as security and surveillance, video-enabled IoT devices, and live event broadcasting.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/amazon-kinesis] Amazon Kinesis can be easily integrated with other AWS services, such as AWS Lambda, Amazon S3, Amazon Redshift, and Amazon OpenSearch.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/amazon-kinesis] This integration enables developers to build end-to-end streaming data processing applications, taking advantage of the extensive AWS ecosystem.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/amazon-kinesis] Amazon Kinesis follows a pay-as-you-go pricing model, with costs depending on the chosen service, data volume, and processing power required.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/amazon-kinesis] AWS provides a free tier for Kinesis Data Streams and Kinesis Data Firehose, allowing users to get started with the services at no cost.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/data-stream] In connection-oriented communication, a **data stream** is the transmission of a sequence of digitally encoded signals to convey information.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/data-stream] Typically, the transmitted symbols are grouped into a series of packets.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/data-stream] Most data transmitted over the Internet is transmitted as a data stream.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/data-stream] Using a mobile phone to have a conversation transmits the sound as a data stream.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/data-stream] 2. $\Delta$ is a sequence of positive real time intervals.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/data-stream] Data Stream contains different sets of data, that depend on the chosen data format.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/data-stream] A **data point** is a tag that collects information about a certain action, performed by a user on a website.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/data-stream] Data points exists in two types, the values of which are used to create appropriate audiences.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/data-stream] Information gathered out of websites are based on user behavior.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/data-stream] Data providers deliver both personal or non-personal information.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] A properly designed ETL system extracts data from source systems and enforces data type and data validity standards and ensures it conforms structurally to the requirements of the output.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] Some ETL systems can also deliver data in a presentation-ready format so that application developers can build applications and end users can make decisions.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] The ETL process is often used in data warehousing.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] ETL systems commonly integrate data from multiple applications (systems), typically developed and supported by different vendors or hosted on separate computer hardware.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] The separate systems containing the original data are frequently managed and operated by different stakeholders.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] For example, a cost accounting system may combine data from payroll, sales, and purchasing.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] ETL and its variant ELT (extract, load, transform), are increasingly used in cloud-based data warehousing.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] Applications involve not only batch processing, but also real-time streaming.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] ETL processing involves extracting the data from the source system(s).
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] In many cases, this represents the most important aspect of ETL, since extracting data correctly sets the stage for the success of subsequent processes.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] Most data-warehousing projects combine data from different source systems.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] Each separate system may also use a different data organization and/or format.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] The streaming of the extracted data source and loading on-the-fly to the destination database is another way of performing ETL when no intermediate data storage is required.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] An intrinsic part of the extraction involves data validation to confirm whether the data pulled from the sources has the correct/expected values in a given domain (such as a pattern/default or list of values).
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] If the data fails the validation rules, it is rejected entirely or in part.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] The rejected data is ideally reported back to the source system for further analysis to identify and to rectify incorrect records or perform data wrangling.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] In the data transformation stage, a series of rules or functions are applied to the extracted data in order to prepare it for loading into the end target.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] An important function of transformation is data cleansing, which aims to pass only "proper" data to the target.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] The challenge when different systems interact is in the relevant systems' interfacing and communicating.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] Character sets that may be available in one system may not be in others.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] The load phase loads the data into the end target, which can be any data store including a simple delimited flat file or a data warehouse.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] Depending on the requirements of the organization, this process varies widely.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] Some data warehouses may overwrite existing information with cumulative information; updating extracted data is frequently done on a daily, weekly, or monthly basis.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] Other data warehouses (or even other parts of the same data warehouse) may add new data in a historical form at regular intervals – for example, hourly.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] To understand this, consider a data warehouse that is required to maintain sales records of the last year.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] This data warehouse overwrites any data older than a year with newer data.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] However, the entry of data for any one year window is made in a historical manner.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] The timing and scope to replace or append are strategic design choices dependent on the time available and the business needs.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] More complex systems can maintain a history and audit trail of all changes to the data loaded in the data warehouse.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] As the load phase interacts with a database, the constraints defined in the database schema – as well as in triggers activated upon data load – apply (for example, uniqueness, referential integrity, mandatory fields), which also contribute to the overall data quality performance of the ETL process.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] Audit reports (for example, on compliance with business rules.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] Archive (Extreme, space-efficient compression for very rarely used, old data.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] ETL processes can involve considerable complexity, and significant operational problems can occur with improperly designed ETL systems.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] The range of data values or data quality in an operational system may exceed the expectations of designers at the time validation and transformation rules are specified.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] Data profiling of a source during data analysis can identify the data conditions that must be managed by transform rules specifications, leading to an amendment of validation rules explicitly and implicitly implemented in the ETL process.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] Data warehouses are typically assembled from a variety of data sources with different formats and purposes.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] As such, ETL is a key process to bring all the data together in a standard, homogeneous environment.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] Design analysis should establish the scalability of an ETL system across the lifetime of its usage – including understanding the volumes of data that must be processed within service level agreements.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] The time available to extract from source systems may change, which may mean the same amount of data may have to be processed in less time.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] Some ETL systems have to scale to process terabytes of data to update data warehouses with tens of terabytes of data.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] Increasing volumes of data may require designs that can scale from daily batch to multiple-day micro batch to integration with message queues or real-time change-data-capture for continuous transformation and update.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] Unique keys play an important part in all relational databases, as they tie everything together.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] A unique key is a column that identifies a given entity, whereas a foreign key is a column in another table that refers to a primary key.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] Keys can comprise several columns, in which case they are composite keys.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] In many cases, the primary key is an auto-generated integer that has no meaning for the business entity being represented, but solely exists for the purpose of the relational database – commonly referred to as a surrogate key.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] As there is usually more than one data source getting loaded into the warehouse, the keys are an important concern to be addressed.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] For example: customers might be represented in several data sources, with their Social Security number as the primary key in one source, their phone number in another, and a surrogate in the third.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] Yet a data warehouse may require the consolidation of all the customer information into one dimension.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] A recommended way to deal with the concern involves adding a warehouse surrogate key, which is used as a foreign key from the fact table.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] Usually, updates occur to a dimension's source data, which must be reflected in the data warehouse.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] If the primary key of the source data is required for reporting, the dimension already contains that piece of information for each row.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] If the source data uses a surrogate key, the warehouse must keep track of it even though it is never used in queries or reports; it is done by creating a lookup table that contains the warehouse surrogate key and the originating key.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] This way, the dimension is not polluted with surrogates from various source systems, while the ability to update is preserved.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] The lookup table is used in different ways depending on the nature of the source data.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] A new dimension row is added with the new state of the source system, while the previous dimension row is updated to reflect it is no longer active and time of deactivation.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] ETL vendors benchmark their record-systems at multiple TB (terabytes) per hour (or ~1 GB per second) using powerful servers with multiple CPUs, multiple hard drives, multiple gigabit-network connections, and much memory.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] In real life, the slowest part of an ETL process usually occurs in the database load phase.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] Databases may perform slowly because they have to take care of concurrency, integrity maintenance, and indices.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] Still, even using bulk operations, database access is usually the bottleneck in the ETL process.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] Whether to do certain operations in the database or outside may involve a trade-off.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] For example, removing duplicates using `distinct` may be slow in the database; thus, it makes sense to do it outside.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] On the other side, if using `distinct` significantly (x100) decreases the number of rows to be extracted, then it makes sense to remove duplications as early as possible in the database before unloading data.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] A common source of problems in ETL is a big number of dependencies among ETL jobs.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] For example, job "B" cannot start while job "A" is not finished.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] One can usually achieve better performance by visualizing all processes on a graph, and trying to reduce the graph making maximum use of parallelism, and making "chains" of consecutive processing as short as possible.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] Again, partitioning of big tables and their indices can really help.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] Another common issue occurs when the data are spread among several databases, and processing is done in those databases sequentially.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] Sometimes database replication may be involved as a method of copying data between databases – it can significantly slow down the whole process.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] This approach allows processing to take maximum advantage of parallelism.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] For example, if you need to load data into two databases, you can run the loads in parallel (instead of loading into the first – and then replicating into the second).
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] Sometimes processing must take place sequentially.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] For example, dimensional (reference) data are needed before one can get and validate the rows for main "fact" tables.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] Some ETL software implementations include parallel processing.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] This enables a number of methods to improve overall performance of ETL when dealing with large volumes of data.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] All three types of parallelism usually operate combined in a single job or task.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] An additional difficulty comes with making sure that the data being uploaded is relatively consistent.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] Because multiple source databases may have different update cycles (some may be updated every few minutes, while others may take days or weeks), an ETL system may be required to hold back certain data until all sources are synchronized.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] Likewise, where a warehouse may have to be reconciled to the contents in a source system or with the general ledger, establishing synchronization and reconciliation points becomes necessary.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] Data warehousing procedures usually subdivide a big ETL process into smaller pieces running sequentially or in parallel.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] To keep track of data flows, it makes sense to tag each data row with "row_id", and tag each piece of the process with "run_id".
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] In case of a failure, having these IDs help to roll back and rerun the failed piece.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] Best practice also calls for *checkpoints*, which are states when certain phases of the process are completed.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] Once at a checkpoint, it is a good idea to write everything to disk, clean out some temporary files, log the state, etc.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] An established ETL framework may improve connectivity and scalability.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] A good ETL tool must be able to communicate with the many different relational databases and read the various file formats used throughout an organization.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] ETL tools have started to migrate into enterprise application integration, or even enterprise service bus, systems that now cover much more than just the extraction, transformation, and loading of data.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] Many ETL vendors now have data profiling, data quality, and metadata capabilities.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] A common use case for ETL tools include converting CSV files to formats readable by relational databases.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] A typical translation of millions of records is facilitated by ETL tools that enable users to input CSV-like data feeds/files and import them into a database with as little code as possible.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] ETL tools are typically used by a broad range of professionals – from students in computer science looking to quickly import large data sets to database architects in charge of company account management, ETL tools have become a convenient tool that can be relied on to get maximum performance.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] ETL tools in most cases contain a GUI that helps users conveniently transform data, using a visual data mapper, as opposed to writing large programs to parse files and modify data types.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] While ETL tools have traditionally been for developers and IT staff, research firm Gartner wrote that the new trend is to provide these capabilities to business users so they can themselves create connections and data integrations when needed, rather than going to the IT staff.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] Gartner refers to these non-technical users as Citizen Integrators.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] In online transaction processing (OLTP) applications, changes from individual OLTP instances are detected and logged into a snapshot, or batch, of updates.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] An ETL instance can be used to periodically collect all of these batches, transform them into a common format, and load them into a data lake or warehouse.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] Data virtualization can be used to advance ETL processing.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] The application of data virtualization to ETL allowed solving the most common ETL tasks of data migration and application integration for multiple dispersed data sources.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] Virtual ETL operates with the abstracted representation of the objects or entities gathered from the variety of relational, semi-structured, and unstructured data sources.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] ETL tools can leverage object-oriented modeling and work with entities' representations persistently stored in a centrally located hub-and-spoke architecture.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] Such a collection that contains representations of the entities or objects gathered from the data sources for ETL processing is called a metadata repository and it can reside in memory or be made persistent.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] By using a persistent metadata repository, ETL tools can transition from one-time projects to persistent middleware, performing data harmonization and data profiling consistently and in near-real time.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] Extract, load, transform (ELT) is a variant of ETL where the extracted data is loaded into the target system first.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] The architecture for the analytics pipeline shall also consider where to cleanse and enrich data as well as how to conform dimensions.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] Some of the benefits of an ELT process include speed and the ability to more easily handle both unstructured and structured data.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] Ralph Kimball and Joe Caserta's book *The Data Warehouse ETL Toolkit*, (Wiley, 2004), which is used as a textbook for courses teaching ETL processes in data warehousing, addressed this issue.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] Cloud-based data warehouses like Amazon Redshift, Google BigQuery, Microsoft Azure Synapse Analytics, and Snowflake provide highly scalable computing power.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] This lets businesses forgo preload transformations and replicate raw data into their data warehouses, where it can transform them as needed using SQL.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] After having used ELT, data may be processed further and stored in a data mart.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] Most data integration tools skew towards ETL, while ELT is popular in database and data warehouse appliances.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/extract-transform-load] Similarly, it is possible to perform TEL (Transform, Extract, Load) where data is first transformed on a blockchain (as a way of recording changes to data, e.g., token burning) before extracting and loading into another data store.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/real-time-data] Real-time data is not the same as dynamic data.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/real-time-data] Real-time data can be dynamic (e.g. a variable indicating current location) or static (e.g. a fresh log entry indicating location at a specific time).
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/real-time-data] Real-time economic data, and other official statistics, are often based on preliminary estimates, and therefore are frequently adjusted as better estimates become available.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/real-time-data] These later adjusted data are called "revised data".
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/real-time-data] The terms real-time economic data and real-time economic analysis were coined by Francis X.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/real-time-data] In order to better understand the accuracy of economic data and its effects on economic decisions, some economic organizations, such as the Federal Reserve Bank of St.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/real-time-data] Louis, Federal Reserve Bank of Philadelphia and the Euro-Area Business Cycle Network (EABCN), have made databases available that contain both real-time data and subsequent revised estimates of the same data.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/real-time-data] Real-time bidding is programmatic real-time auctions that sell digital-ad impressions.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/real-time-data] Entities on both the buying and selling sides require almost instantaneous access to data in order to make decisions, forcing real-time data to the forefront of their needs.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/real-time-data] To support these needs, new strategies and technologies, such Druid have arisen and are quickly evolving.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] In computer science, **stream processing** (also known as **event stream processing**, **data stream processing**, or **distributed stream processing**) is a programming paradigm which views streams, or sequences of events in time, as the central input and output objects of computation.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] Stream processing encompasses dataflow programming, reactive programming, and distributed data processing.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] Stream processing systems use streaming algorithms to trace parallel processing for data streams.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] The stream processing paradigm simplifies parallel software and hardware by restricting the parallel computation that can be performed.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] Given a sequence of data (a *stream*), a series of operations (*kernel functions*) is applied to each element in the stream.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] Kernel functions are usually pipelined, and optimal local on-chip memory reuse is attempted, in order to minimize the loss in bandwidth, associated with external memory interaction.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] *Uniform streaming*, where one kernel function is applied to all elements in the stream, is typical.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] Since the kernel and stream abstractions expose data dependencies, compiler tools can fully automate and optimize on-chip management tasks.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] Stream processing hardware can use scoreboarding, for example, to initiate a direct memory access (DMA) when dependencies become known.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] The elimination of manual DMA management reduces software complexity, and an associated elimination for hardware cached I/O, reduces the data area expanse that has to be involved with service by specialized computational units such as arithmetic logic units.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] During the 1980s stream processing was explored within dataflow programming.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] An example is the language SISAL (Streams and Iteration in a Single Assignment Language).
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] Stream processing is essentially a compromise, driven by a data-centric model that works very well for traditional DSP or GPU-type applications (such as image, video and digital signal processing) but less so for general purpose processing with more randomized data access (such as databases).
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] By sacrificing some flexibility in the model, the implications allow easier, faster and more efficient execution.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] Depending on the context, processor design may be tuned for maximum efficiency or a trade-off for flexibility.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] For each record we can only read from the input, perform operations on it, and write to the output.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] It is permissible to have multiple inputs and multiple outputs, but never a piece of memory that is both readable and writable.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] By way of illustration, the following code fragments demonstrate detection of patterns within event streams.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] The first is an example of processing a data stream using a continuous SQL query (a query that executes forever processing arriving data based on timestamps and window duration).
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] This code fragment illustrates a JOIN of two data streams, one for stock orders, and one for the resulting stock trades.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] The query outputs a stream of all Orders matched by a Trade within one second of the Order being placed.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] The output stream is sorted by timestamp, in this case, the timestamp from the Orders stream.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] Another sample code fragment detects weddings among a flow of external "events" such as church bells ringing, the appearance of a man in a tuxedo or morning suit, a woman in a flowing white gown and rice flying through the air.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] A "complex" or "composite" event is what one infers from the individual simple events: a wedding is happening.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] Basic computers started from a sequential execution paradigm.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] Traditional CPUs are SISD based, which means they conceptually perform only one operation at a time.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] As the computing needs of the world evolved, the amount of data to be managed increased very quickly.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] It was obvious that the sequential programming model could not cope with the increased need for processing power.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] Various efforts have been spent on finding alternative ways to perform massive amounts of computations but the only solution was to exploit some level of parallel execution.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] The result of those efforts was SIMD, a programming paradigm which allowed applying one instruction to multiple instances of (different) data.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] Most of the time, SIMD was being used in a SWAR environment.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] By using more complicated structures, one could also have MIMD parallelism.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] Although those two paradigms were efficient, real-world implementations were plagued with limitations from memory alignment problems to synchronization issues and limited parallelism.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] Only few SIMD processors survived as stand-alone components; most were embedded in standard CPUs.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] Consider a simple program adding up two arrays containing 100 4-component vectors (i.e.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] This is the sequential paradigm that is most familiar.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] Variations do exist (such as inner loops, structures and such), but they ultimately boil down to that construct.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] It assumes the instruction `vector_sum` works.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] Although this is what happens with instruction intrinsics, much information is actually not taken into account here such as the number of vector components and their data format.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] You can see however, this method reduces the number of decoded instructions from *numElements * componentsPerElement* to *numElements*.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] The number of jump instructions is also decreased, as the loop is run fewer times.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] These gains result from the parallel execution of the four mathematical operations.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] What happened however is that the packed SIMD register holds a certain amount of data so it's not possible to get more parallelism.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] The speed up is somewhat limited by the assumption we made of performing four parallel operations (please note this is common for both AltiVec and SSE).
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] In this paradigm, the whole dataset is defined, rather than each component block being defined separately.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] Describing the set of data is assumed to be in the first two rows.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] After that, the result is inferred from the sources and kernel.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] For simplicity, there's a 1:1 mapping between input and output data but this does not need to be.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] Applied kernels can also be much more complex.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] An implementation of this paradigm can "unroll" a loop internally.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] This allows throughput to scale with chip complexity, easily utilizing hundreds of ALUs.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] The elimination of complex data patterns makes much of this extra power available.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] While stream processing is a branch of SIMD/MIMD processing, they must not be confused.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] Although SIMD implementations can often work in a "streaming" manner, their performance is not comparable: the model envisions a very different usage pattern which allows far greater performance by itself.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] It has been noted that when applied on generic processors such as standard CPU, only a 1.5x speedup can be reached.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] By contrast, ad-hoc stream processors easily reach over 10x performance, mainly attributed to the more efficient memory access and higher levels of parallel processing.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] Although there are various degrees of flexibility allowed by the model, stream processors usually impose some limitations on the kernel or stream size.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] For example, consumer hardware often lacks the ability to perform high-precision math, lacks complex indirection chains or presents lower limits on the number of instructions which can be executed.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] Stanford University stream processing projects included the Stanford Real-Time Programmable Shading Project started in 1999.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] A prototype called Imagine was developed in 2002.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] A project called Merrimac ran until about 2004.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] AT&T also researched stream-enhanced processors as graphics processing units rapidly evolved in both speed and functionality.[1] Since these early days, dozens of stream processing languages have been developed, as well as specialized hardware.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] The most immediate challenge in the realm of parallel processing does not lie as much in the type of hardware architecture used, but in how easy it will be to program the system in question in a real-world environment with acceptable performance.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] Machines like Imagine use a straightforward single-threaded model with automated dependencies, memory allocation and DMA scheduling.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] This in itself is a result of the research at MIT and Stanford in finding an optimal *layering of tasks* between programmer, tools and hardware.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] Programmers beat tools in mapping algorithms to parallel hardware, and tools beat programmers in figuring out smartest memory allocation schemes, etc.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] Of particular concern are MIMD designs such as Cell, for which the programmer needs to deal with application partitioning across multiple cores and deal with process synchronization and load balancing.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] A drawback of SIMD programming was the issue of array-of-structures (AoS) and structure-of-arrays (SoA).
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] When multiple of these structures exist in memory they are placed end to end creating an arrays in an *array of structures* (AoS) topology.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] This means that should some algorithm be applied to the location of each particle in turn it must skip over memory locations containing the other attributes.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] If these attributes are not needed this results in wasteful usage of the CPU cache.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] Additionally, a SIMD instruction will typically expect the data it will operate on to be contiguous in memory, the elements may also need to be aligned.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] By moving the memory location of the data out of the structure data can be better organised for efficient access in a stream and for SIMD instructions to operate one.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] A *structure of arrays* (SoA), as shown below, can allow this.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] Instead of holding the data in the structure, it holds only pointers (memory locations) for the data.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] Shortcomings are that if multiple attributes to of an object are to be operated on they might now be distant in memory and so result in a cache miss.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] The aligning and any needed padding lead to increased memory usage.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] Overall, memory management may be more complicated if structures are added and removed for example.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] For stream processors, the usage of structures is encouraged.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] From an application point of view, all the attributes can be defined with some flexibility.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] Taking GPUs as reference, there is a set of attributes (at least 16) available.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] For each attribute, the application can state the number of components and the format of the components (but only primitive data types are supported for now).
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] The various attributes are then attached to a memory block, possibly defining a *stride* between 'consecutive' elements of the same attributes, effectively allowing interleaved data.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] When the GPU begins the stream processing, it will *gather* all the various attributes in a single set of parameters (usually this looks like a structure or a "magic global variable"), performs the operations and *scatters* the results to some memory area for later processing (or retrieving).
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] More modern stream processing frameworks provide a FIFO like interface to structure data as a literal stream.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] This abstraction provides a means to specify data dependencies implicitly while enabling the runtime/hardware to take full advantage of that knowledge for efficient computation.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] One of the simplest and most efficient stream processing modalities to date for C++, is RaftLib, which enables linking independent compute kernels together as a data flow graph using C++ stream operators.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] Apart from specifying streaming applications in high-level languages, models of computation (MoCs) also have been widely used as dataflow models and process-based models.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] Historically, CPUs began implementing various tiers of memory access optimizations because of the ever-increasing performance when compared to relatively slow growing external memory bandwidth.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] As this gap widened, big amounts of die area were dedicated to hiding memory latencies.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] Since fetching information and opcodes to those few ALUs is expensive, very little die area is dedicated to actual mathematical machinery (as a rough estimation, consider it to be less than 10%).
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] A similar architecture exists on stream processors but thanks to the new programming model, the amount of transistors dedicated to management is actually very little.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] Beginning from a whole system point of view, stream processors usually exist in a controlled environment.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] GPUs do exist on an add-in board (this seems to also apply to Imagine).
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] CPUs continue do the job of managing system resources, running applications, and such.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] The stream processor is usually equipped with a fast, efficient, proprietary memory bus (crossbar switches are now common, multi-buses have been employed in the past).
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] The exact amount of memory lanes is dependent on the market range.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] As this is written, there are still 64-bit wide interconnections around (entry-level).
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] Most mid-range models use a fast 128-bit crossbar switch matrix (4 or 2 segments), while high-end models deploy huge amounts of memory (actually up to 512 MB) with a slightly slower crossbar that is 256 bits wide.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] By contrast, standard processors from Intel Pentium to some Athlon 64 have only a single 64-bit wide data bus.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] Memory access patterns are much more predictable.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] While arrays do exist, their dimension is fixed at kernel invocation.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] The thing which most closely matches a multiple pointer indirection is an *indirection chain*, which is however guaranteed to finally read or write from a specific memory area (inside a stream).
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] Because of the SIMD nature of the stream processor's execution units (ALUs clusters), read/write operations are expected to happen in bulk, so memories are optimized for high bandwidth rather than low latency (this is a difference from Rambus and DDR SDRAM, for example).
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] This also allows for efficient memory bus negotiations.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] Most (90%) of a stream processor's work is done on-chip, requiring only 1% of the global data to be stored to memory.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] This is where knowing the kernel temporaries and dependencies pays.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] Internally, a stream processor features some clever communication and management circuits but what's interesting is the *Stream Register File* (SRF).
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] This is conceptually a large cache in which stream data is stored to be transferred to external memory in bulks.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] As a cache-like software-controlled structure to the various ALUs, the SRF is shared between all the various ALU clusters.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] The key concept and innovation here done with Stanford's Imagine chip is that the compiler is able to automate and allocate memory in an optimal way, fully transparent to the programmer.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] The dependencies between kernel functions and data is known through the programming model which enables the compiler to perform flow analysis and optimally pack the SRFs.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] Commonly, this cache and DMA management can take up the majority of a project's schedule, something the stream processor (or at least Imagine) totally automates.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] Tests done at Stanford showed that the compiler did an as well or better job at scheduling memory than if you hand tuned the thing with much effort.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] There is proof; there can be a lot of clusters because inter-cluster communication is assumed to be rare.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] Internally however, each cluster can efficiently exploit a much lower amount of ALUs because intra-cluster communication is common and thus needs to be highly efficient.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] To keep those ALUs fetched with data, each ALU is equipped with local register files (LRFs), which are basically its usable registers.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] This three-tiered data access pattern, makes it easy to keep temporary data away from slow memories, thus making the silicon implementation highly efficient and power-saving.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] Although an order of magnitude speedup can be reasonably expected (even from mainstream GPUs when computing in a streaming manner), not all applications benefit from this.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] Communication latencies are actually the biggest problem.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] Although PCI Express improved this with full-duplex communications, getting a GPU (and possibly a generic stream processor) to work will possibly take long amounts of time.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] This means it's usually counter-productive to use them for small datasets.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] Because changing the kernel is a rather expensive operation the stream architecture also incurs penalties for small streams, a behaviour referred to as the *short stream effect*.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] Pipelining is a very widespread and heavily used practice on stream processors, with GPUs featuring pipelines exceeding 200 stages.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] The cost for switching settings is dependent on the setting being modified but it is now considered to always be expensive.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] To avoid those problems at various levels of the pipeline, many techniques have been deployed such as "über shaders" and "texture atlases".
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] Those techniques are game-oriented because of the nature of GPUs, but the concepts are interesting for generic stream processing as well.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] Most programming languages for stream processors start with Java, C or C++ and add extensions which provide specific instructions to allow application developers to tag kernels and/or streams.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] This also applies to most shading languages, which can be considered stream programming languages to a certain degree.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/stream-processing] Commercial implementations are either general purpose or tied to specific hardware by a vendor.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] It is usually used in the context of big data in which it is generated by many different sources at high speed.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] Data streaming can also be explained as a technology used to deliver content to devices over the internet, and it allows users to access the content immediately, rather than having to wait for it to be downloaded.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] Big data is forcing many organizations to focus on storage costs, which brings interest to data lakes and data streams.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] Before explaining the benefits of streaming data, it is important to understand the difference between digitization and digitalization.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] Digitiztion is the creation (encoding) of digital information (e.g., a file) using analog information.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] When a digital camera takes a photo, the light entering its lens is the analog information, and the photo file is the digital representation of said light.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] The camera is digitizing the visual information.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] Digitalization describes mainly a socio-technical process, where a society or organization adopts digital forms for data storage.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] Converting analog information in a library (physical books) into digital formats (eBook documents), for example, would be digitalization of said library.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] Within the context of data streaming, media has been digitized since the early 1990s with the adaptation of digital recordings, e.g., storing music and videos in digital forms, while the digitalization of media did not start until the beginning of the 21st century.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] The digital innovation management like Metabott theories mention five characteristics of streaming data: homogenization and decoupling, modularity, connectivity, digital traces and programmability.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] Homogenization and decoupling. “Because all digital information assumes the same form, it can, at least in principle, be processed by the same technologies.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] Consequently, digitizing has the potential to remove the tight couplings between information types and their storage, transmission, and processing technologies”.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] Within the context of data streaming, this means in theory that one can stream data now from any digital device.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] It also reduces the demand and use of music and films on CDs for example.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] One of the consequences of homogenization & decoupling is the decline of marginal costs.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] The marginal cost of data streaming is because it solely uses digital information, which can be transmitted, stored, and computed in fast and low-cost ways.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] An example of an industry that has low marginal costs due to data streaming is the music industry.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] Producers can now digitize songs and upload them on Spotify, instead of paying for the creation of the physical albums and distributing them.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] Another consequence is convergent user experience, meaning that previously separated experiences are now brought together in one product.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] Data streaming is also modular, because systems components may be separated and recombined mainly for flexibility and variety.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] Data streaming works in different application versions and systems such as iOS.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] It is also possible to change the speed of data streaming.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] A consequence of modularity is the creation of platforms.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] Data streaming platforms bring together analysis of information, but more importantly, they are able to integrate data between different sources (Myers, 2016).
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] IBM streams for example is an analytics platform that enables the applications developed by users to gather, analyze and correlate information that comes to them from a variety of sources (IBM).
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] The third characteristic, connectivity, describes that a digital technology not only connects applications, devices and users but also connects customers and firms.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] Streaming services for example connects a vast collection of music and films of ‘producers’ with their consumers, so how music on Spotify can easily reach a vast group of consumers.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] Another example would be data of transport vehicles that can also be connected to firms with streaming applications, via vehicle-to-roadside communications.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] UPS does this for example to ‘calculate’ the optimal delivery routes by streaming real time big data and thereby reducing time to deliver packages.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] Interoperability, which is the ability of a product or system to work with other products or systems, is a consequence of connectivity.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] For instance, the music industry is interoperable, because some music platforms have integrated social media platforms.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] Another of connectivity is network externality.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] This means that the value of a good to a user increases with the number of other users (installed base) of the same or similar good.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] Data streaming technology can utilize network externalities, because it brings together supply and demand of large networks of creators and consumers.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] This is very much the case at popcorn time, a service where people can stream latest movies on demand.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] These streams work better when people have used their content.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] The latter has to do with the fact that if one streams content he/she automatically also down/uploads content.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] While a streaming service is being used it leaves Digital Traces, which simply describes the fact that all digital technologies leave a digital trace from the user.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] In the past, when media was sold, the seller/provider only had information about the transaction itself.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] With data streaming it has become possible to actually track the behaviour of the users because it occurs in real time, directly from the distributor/providers.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] Morris and Powers describe this as opening the 'black box' of consumption.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] Providers of streaming services, for example, are now able to track detailed consuming behavior of the user, which in turn, they use to influence the user's decision-making process by creating algorithms to further develop a service.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] This kind of streaming has changed the way people consume media, which in time offered new possibilities for new ideas.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] These are also referred to as wakes of innovation and occur in places one would not initially expect.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] For instance, data streaming has enabled the development of sensors, for example that are used in a lot of sectors for different purposes.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] In the manufacturing sector data streaming is used for real-time analysis to improve operations.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] In healthcare sector sensors are being used for connected medical devices to create hubs of patients and healthcare providers, that can trigger alerts when a patient has a medical emergency.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] Finally, programmability, a characteristic that describes that an innovative digital technology can be reprogrammed, improved and/or updated.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] Consequences of programmability are emerging functionalities.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] The most applicable functionality is incompleteness, which means that products and services are never finished, which is the case for data streaming because suppliers will keep refreshing their models .
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] However, a more influential consequence of the programmability, and also of connectivity is the servitization of digital media content.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] Data streaming has caused a shift towards pay for use instead of pay for ownership;.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] This is happening in the video and music streaming industry, think of Netflix or Spotify.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] You have to pay to use the service, instead of owning a product.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] This was the case with buying an album or DVD, whereas now it is possible to access thousands of songs or movies.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] Data streaming is becoming more useful and necessary in today's world and is being applied in a broad range of industries, some of which that have been already mentioned in examples such as the medical or transportation industry.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] Besides these examples, there are probably many more applications for data streaming.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] However, data streaming has had the biggest implications for the audio, video and telecom industry because of the creation of streaming services.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] Streaming services have majorly influenced how people consume their media nowadays.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] Since the streaming services have had the most significant impact using the data streaming technology, this will be the main focus further on this page.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] The process of technological convergence, which appears because different industries increasingly rely on the same set of technological skills in their production processes, leads to closer relations between markets that was previously not highly related.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] For example, social media platforms such as Facebook and Twitter are providing live-streaming services, which allows global news publishers to connect directly with the right audiences as well as a far wider range of audiences than they otherwise would have reached.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] This has led to a change in which how and where news publishers are interacting with their audiences, and how they use social media services to deliver their service.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] An industry that is impacted by data streaming is the Video Streaming industry.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] Consumers are now demanding videos to be available at immediate request, meaning that it is no longer only the quality resolution of image that acts as important performance metrics in the media industry, but also how quickly video starts to play.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] The video industry underwent some of the same changes as the music industry.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] The video industry gained revenue by selling DVDs to customers and selling rights to cinemas and television channels.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] In 1997, the first online distributors began, but this was still small over a decade later mainly due to lower quality compared to hardcopy films.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] The third wave of streaming services such as Netflix, iTunes, Hulu, Amazon and Blockbuster have changed the film market.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] The digitization, digitalization and underlying technologies of streaming have created these streaming services which essentially caused this disruption.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] With the rise of streaming firms in the film industry, the sales of physical DVDs vanished completely.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] An important difference between the music and film industry is that within the film industry, streaming services such as iTunes and Netflix are ‘destroying’ revenue (Sullivan, 2009).
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] Because of this less films are produced and consequently there are less jobs in this industry.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] On contrary, cinemas are still important in the film industry, but the share of movies and series that are streamed by customers is rising very fast.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] It replaced the DVD, changed the performance metrics of the incumbents and can thus be seen as disruptive.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] Another impacted industry is the Music Streaming industry.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] In 2017, streaming accounted for 43% of revenues in the music industry, and this was the third year of consecutive growth.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] New music streaming services such as Spotify and Apple Music challenges the traditional label companies, which are now risking to be outcompeted by new business models.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] Before the rapid adaption of streaming, in 2000 the music industry was experiencing what turned out to be a 15-year-long continued stagnation in revenue, which was due to the high CD prices needed to cover the costs of record labels.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] In 2015, the streaming technology overtook the market by allowing revenues to increase by saving costs on labels, and artists to have a more steady income by making money on streams, rather than being reliant on a full album or CD to do well after being published.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] Furthermore, data streaming also has an impact on the Game Streaming industry.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] Game streaming is caused by the considerable growth of cloud computing, which allow gamers to access a greater variety of games without having to own expensive hardware.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] Cloud computing operates as an enabler to the development of game streaming, where hardware and content is accessed from the cloud, leading to a change in offering greater flexibility in content distribution.
[src:aws-kinesis-firehose/streaming-data] Game streaming allowed by cloud technology will drive changes in the gaming industry, where it is the hardware configuration of machines in the cloud that will be the developers, cost and time will be reduced to develop a greater ability of user reach around the world.
